mos.key_properties.basic_approximations"}], "subTopics": [{"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.resolution", "properties": [{"values": ["12.0 km x 12.0 km"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.resolution.canonical_horizontal_resolution"}, {"values": ["23"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.resolution.number_of_vertical_levels"}, {"values": ["True"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.resolution.high_top"}]}, {"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.timestepping", "properties": [{"values": ["24"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.timestepping.timestep_dynamics"}, {"values": ["1800"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.timestepping.timestep_shortwave_radiative_transfer"}, {"values": ["1800"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.timestepping.timestep_longwave_radiative_transfer"}]}, {"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.orography", "properties": [{"values": ["fixed: present day"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.orography.type"}]}, {"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.Topic"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.tuning_applied", "properties": [{"values": ["The starting set-up was identical to that of the CORDEX-CORE. 5 year simulations [1999-2005] were run to test the configuration and compare to the EOBS (using seasonal biases, and PDFs). The simulations were repeated by changing cloud, convection, and other parameters (one at a time) in order to minimize the bias. The final configuration used was the best configuration obtained in the 6-month time-frame allocated for the tuning."], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.tuning_applied.description"}, {"values": ["seasonal bias[tas, pr, P99]; PDFs[tas, pr]"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.atmos.key_properties.tuning_applied.regional_metrics_used"}]}]}}], "canonicalID": "ictp-regcm4-6", "keyProperties": {"propertySets": [{"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicPropertySet"}, "specializationID": "cordex.toplevel.key_properties.model_type", "properties": [{"values": ["Regional Atmospheric Climate Model"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.toplevel.key_properties.model_type.model_family"}, {"values": ["A new version of the RegCM regional climate modeling system, RegCM4, has been recently developed and made available for public use. Compared to previous versions, RegCM4 includes new land surface, planetary boundary layer, and air\u2013sea flux schemes, a mixed convection and tropical band configuration, modifications to the pre-existing radiative transfer and boundary layer schemes, and a full upgrade of the model code towards improved flexibility, portability, and user friendliness. The model can be interactively coupled to a 1D lake model, a simplified aerosol scheme (including organic carbon, black carbon, SO4, dust, and sea spray), and a gas phase chemistry module (CBM-Z). After a general description of the model, a series of test experiments are presented over 4 domains prescribed under the CORDEX framework (Africa, South America, East Asia, and Europe) to provide illustrative examples of the model behavior and sensitivities under different climatic regimes. These experiments indicate that, overall, RegCM4 shows an improved performance in several respects compared to previous versions, although further testing by the user community is needed to fully explore its sensitivities and range of applications."], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.toplevel.key_properties.model_type.details"}]}, {"meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicPropertySet"}, "specializationID": "cordex.toplevel.key_properties.genealogy", "properties": [{"values": ["2012"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.toplevel.key_properties.genealogy.year_released"}, {"values": ["RegCM3"], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.toplevel.key_properties.genealogy.previous_name"}, {"values": ["The basic model dynamics have remained the same as in RegCM3.  In RegCM4 the radiative cloud representation is modified by first calculating the total cloud cover at a given grid point and then calculating the surface fluxes separately for the cloudy and clear sky portions of the grid bo to account for the occurrence of fractional clear sky at a given grid box. In RegCM4, the contribution of the infrared spectrum was added following Solmon et al. (2008).  The existing PBL scheme (Holtslag et al. 1990), underwent various modifications, and second a new PBL scheme, the University of Washington PBL (Grenier & Bretherton 2001, Bretherton et al. 2004), was implemented. The capability of running different convection schemes over land and ocean, a configuration referred to as \u2018mixed convection', was added. The resolved scale precipitation scheme remains unchanged with the exception of some parameter settings. 2 new land use types were added to BATS to represent urban and suburban environments, and  the option to use the Community Land Model. The prognostic SST scheme described by Zeng & Beljaars (2005) was implemented in RegCM4. More information is available in Giorgi et al (2012). "], "meta": {"type": "cim.2.science.TopicProperty"}, "specializationID": "cordex.toplevel.key_properties.genealogy.difference_to_previous"}]}, {"meta": {"type"